---
import SiteLayout from '../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro';

const schema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@graph": [
    {
      "@type": "Article",
      "headline": "Nutrition Fundamentals: Calories, Macros & Meal Planning",
      "description": "Everything about nutrition: TDEE, BMR, macronutrients, protein needs, hydration, and building a sustainable meal plan.",
      "author": {
        "@type": "Organization",
        "name": "PhotonBuilder Health"
      },
      "url": "https://photonbuilder.com/health/guide-nutrition-complete"
    },
    {
      "@type": "FAQPage",
      "mainEntity": [
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How many calories should I eat?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Your daily calorie needs depend on your Total Daily Energy Expenditure (TDEE). If you want to lose weight, eat 300-500 calories below your TDEE. To gain muscle, eat 200-500 calories above it. For maintenance, eat at your TDEE."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How much protein do I need per day?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "For active individuals or those looking to build muscle, a standard recommendation is 0.7 to 1 gram of protein per pound of body weight. For general health, 0.4 to 0.5 grams per pound is sufficient."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How much water should I drink?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "A general baseline is half your body weight in ounces per day, but you should add 16-24 oz per hour of intense exercise, especially in hot climates."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Do carbs make you fat?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "No. Consuming more calories than you burn (a caloric surplus) is what causes weight gain. Carbs are simply a source of energy and do not inherently cause fat gain unless overconsumed."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Does meal timing matter?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "For most people, overall daily caloric and macronutrient intake is far more important than exactly when you eat. Meal timing only becomes crucial for elite athletes or specific training regimens."
          }
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
};
---

<SiteLayout
  site="bodycount"
  title="Nutrition Fundamentals: Calories, Macros & Meal Planning"
  description="Everything about nutrition: TDEE, BMR, macronutrients, protein needs, hydration, and building a sustainable meal plan."
  canonical="https://photonbuilder.com/health/guide-nutrition-complete"
  schema={schema}
>
  <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-5 py-12">
    <h1 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-extrabold text-[var(--accent-color)] mb-4 text-center">Nutrition Fundamentals: Calories, Macros & Meal Planning</h1>
    <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] mb-12 text-lg md:text-xl text-center max-w-2xl mx-auto">
      Mastering your diet doesn't require complex science. Understanding the basic principles of energy balance, macronutrients, and hydration is all you need to reach your health goals.
    </p>

    <!-- Table of Contents (Optional, but good for long guides) -->
    <div class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-xl p-6 mb-12 shadow-sm">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-white mb-4">Table of Contents</h2>
      <ul class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-2 text-[var(--text-secondary)]">
        <li><a href="#energy-balance" class="hover:text-[var(--accent-color)] transition-colors">1. Energy Balance 101</a></li>
        <li><a href="#calculating-tdee" class="hover:text-[var(--accent-color)] transition-colors">2. Calculating Your TDEE</a></li>
        <li><a href="#macronutrients" class="hover:text-[var(--accent-color)] transition-colors">3. Macronutrients Deep Dive</a></li>
        <li><a href="#protein-needs" class="hover:text-[var(--accent-color)] transition-colors">4. Protein: How Much Do You Really Need?</a></li>
        <li><a href="#hydration" class="hover:text-[var(--accent-color)] transition-colors">5. Hydration</a></li>
        <li><a href="#meal-planning" class="hover:text-[var(--accent-color)] transition-colors">6. Meal Planning & Prep</a></li>
        <li><a href="#nutrition-myths" class="hover:text-[var(--accent-color)] transition-colors">7. Common Nutrition Myths</a></li>
        <li><a href="#faq" class="hover:text-[var(--accent-color)] transition-colors">8. Frequently Asked Questions</a></li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <!-- Section 1: Energy Balance -->
    <section id="energy-balance" class="mb-12 scroll-mt-24">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mb-6 border-b border-[var(--border-color)] pb-2">1. Energy Balance 101</h2>
      <div class="space-y-4 text-[var(--text-secondary)]">
        <p>The foundation of all weight management is <strong>Energy Balance</strong>—the relationship between the calories you consume (Energy In) and the calories you burn (Energy Out).</p>

        <div class="bg-[var(--bg-color)] p-5 rounded-lg border border-[var(--border-color)] my-6">
          <ul class="space-y-3">
            <li class="flex items-start">
              <span class="text-[var(--accent-color)] mr-2 font-bold">✓</span>
              <span><strong>Caloric Deficit (Weight Loss):</strong> Energy In &lt; Energy Out.</span>
            </li>
            <li class="flex items-start">
              <span class="text-[var(--accent-color)] mr-2 font-bold">✓</span>
              <span><strong>Maintenance (Weight Stable):</strong> Energy In = Energy Out.</span>
            </li>
            <li class="flex items-start">
              <span class="text-[var(--accent-color)] mr-2 font-bold">✓</span>
              <span><strong>Caloric Surplus (Weight Gain):</strong> Energy In &gt; Energy Out.</span>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <p>Your total daily energy expenditure (TDEE) is made up of several components:</p>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-2 mb-4">
          <li><strong>BMR (Basal Metabolic Rate):</strong> The calories your body burns just to stay alive (organs, breathing, etc.). Accounts for ~60-70% of TDEE. You can calculate yours using our <a href="/health/bmr-calculator" class="text-[var(--accent-color)] hover:underline font-semibold">BMR Calculator</a>.</li>
          <li><strong>NEAT (Non-Exercise Activity Thermogenesis):</strong> Calories burned from daily movement like walking, fidgeting, and chores.</li>
          <li><strong>TEF (Thermic Effect of Food):</strong> The energy required to digest and process food (protein has the highest TEF).</li>
          <li><strong>EAT (Exercise Activity Thermogenesis):</strong> Calories burned during intentional workouts.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>To fully grasp how these factors contribute to weight loss, read our guide on the <a href="/health/calorie-deficit" class="text-[var(--accent-color)] hover:underline font-semibold">Calorie Deficit</a>.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Section 2: Calculating Your TDEE -->
    <section id="calculating-tdee" class="mb-12 scroll-mt-24">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mb-6 border-b border-[var(--border-color)] pb-2">2. Calculating Your TDEE</h2>
      <div class="space-y-4 text-[var(--text-secondary)]">
        <p>Before you can plan your diet, you need a baseline target. Your Total Daily Energy Expenditure (TDEE) is an estimate of your daily caloric burn based on your BMR and activity level.</p>

        <p>Common formulas like Mifflin-St Jeor or Harris-Benedict use your age, weight, height, and gender to estimate BMR, which is then multiplied by an activity factor (usually between 1.2 for sedentary and 1.9 for extremely active).</p>

        <div class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--accent-color)] rounded-xl p-6 my-6 text-center">
          <h3 class="text-white font-bold text-lg mb-2">Find Your Numbers Instantly</h3>
          <p class="mb-4">Take the guesswork out of the math. Use our calculator to get your specific BMR, TDEE, and daily macro targets.</p>
          <a href="/health/tdee-calculator" class="inline-block bg-[var(--accent-color)] text-[var(--bg-color)] font-bold py-3 px-6 rounded-lg hover:opacity-90 transition-opacity">
            Open TDEE Calculator
          </a>
        </div>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-white mt-6 mb-2">Adjusting Over Time</h3>
        <p>Remember that a TDEE calculator provides an <em>estimate</em>. The best way to find your true TDEE is to track your daily calories and morning body weight for 2-3 weeks. If your weight stays the same, that calorie average is your true maintenance level.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Section 3: Macronutrients Deep Dive -->
    <section id="macronutrients" class="mb-12 scroll-mt-24">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mb-6 border-b border-[var(--border-color)] pb-2">3. Macronutrients Deep Dive</h2>
      <div class="space-y-4 text-[var(--text-secondary)]">
        <p>Calories determine your weight, but <strong>macronutrients (macros)</strong> determine your body composition and how you feel. To figure out the right split for you, use our <a href="/health/macro-calculator" class="text-[var(--accent-color)] hover:underline font-semibold">Macro Calculator</a>.</p>

        <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-3 gap-6 mt-8">
          <div class="bg-[var(--bg-color)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-lg p-5">
            <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-white mb-2 flex items-center">
              <span class="bg-red-500/20 text-red-400 w-8 h-8 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center mr-3 text-sm">P</span>
              Protein
            </h3>
            <p class="text-sm mb-3"><strong>4 calories per gram</strong></p>
            <p class="text-sm mb-3">Essential for muscle repair, immune function, and satiety. It prevents muscle loss when in a calorie deficit.</p>
            <p class="text-xs text-[var(--text-secondary)]"><strong>Sources:</strong> Chicken, fish, beef, eggs, tofu, Greek yogurt, lentils.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="bg-[var(--bg-color)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-lg p-5">
            <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-white mb-2 flex items-center">
              <span class="bg-blue-500/20 text-blue-400 w-8 h-8 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center mr-3 text-sm">C</span>
              Carbs
            </h3>
            <p class="text-sm mb-3"><strong>4 calories per gram</strong></p>
            <p class="text-sm mb-3">The body's primary energy source. Vital for high-intensity exercise and brain function.</p>
            <p class="text-xs text-[var(--text-secondary)]"><strong>Sources:</strong> Rice, potatoes, oats, fruits, vegetables, pasta.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="bg-[var(--bg-color)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-lg p-5">
            <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-white mb-2 flex items-center">
              <span class="bg-yellow-500/20 text-yellow-400 w-8 h-8 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center mr-3 text-sm">F</span>
              Fats
            </h3>
            <p class="text-sm mb-3"><strong>9 calories per gram</strong></p>
            <p class="text-sm mb-3">Crucial for hormone regulation (including testosterone), joint health, and absorbing vitamins (A, D, E, K).</p>
            <p class="text-xs text-[var(--text-secondary)]"><strong>Sources:</strong> Olive oil, nuts, avocados, salmon, butter, egg yolks.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Section 4: Protein -->
    <section id="protein-needs" class="mb-12 scroll-mt-24">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mb-6 border-b border-[var(--border-color)] pb-2">4. Protein: How Much Do You Really Need?</h2>
      <div class="space-y-4 text-[var(--text-secondary)]">
        <p>Protein is arguably the most important macronutrient for body composition. But recommendations vary wildly from FDA guidelines to bodybuilder lore.</p>

        <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-2">
          <li><strong>General Health:</strong> 0.4 - 0.5g per pound of body weight.</li>
          <li><strong>Active/Maintenance:</strong> 0.6 - 0.8g per pound of body weight.</li>
          <li><strong>Building Muscle or Cutting:</strong> 0.7 - 1.0g per pound of body weight.</li>
        </ul>

        <p>When you are in a caloric deficit, higher protein intake (closer to 1g/lb) helps preserve lean muscle mass and keeps you feeling full longer.</p>

        <div class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] p-5 rounded-lg border border-[var(--border-color)] mt-6">
          <h3 class="text-white font-bold mb-2">Eating on a Budget?</h3>
          <p class="mb-3">Hitting high protein targets can get expensive. Not all protein sources are created equal when it comes to cost. Check out our analysis on getting the most <a href="/health/protein-per-dollar" class="text-[var(--accent-color)] hover:underline font-semibold">Protein Per Dollar</a> to build a cost-effective grocery list.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Section 5: Hydration -->
    <section id="hydration" class="mb-12 scroll-mt-24">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mb-6 border-b border-[var(--border-color)] pb-2">5. Hydration</h2>
      <div class="space-y-4 text-[var(--text-secondary)]">
        <p>Water is involved in every cellular process in your body. Even mild dehydration (1-2%) can significantly impair physical performance, cognitive function, and digestion.</p>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-white mt-6 mb-2">How Much Should You Drink?</h3>
        <p>The "8 glasses a day" rule is outdated. A better baseline rule of thumb is to drink <strong>half your body weight (in pounds) in ounces of water per day.</strong></p>
        <p>For example, a 200 lb person should aim for roughly 100 oz of water daily. However, you must adjust this based on:</p>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-2">
          <li><strong>Exercise:</strong> Add 16-24 oz per hour of intense activity.</li>
          <li><strong>Climate:</strong> Hot or humid weather increases sweat loss and fluid requirements.</li>
          <li><strong>Electrolytes:</strong> Drinking massive amounts of plain water without replenishing sodium, potassium, and magnesium can lead to hyponatremia. If you sweat heavily, consider electrolyte supplementation.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>To calculate a specific target based on your weight and activity level, use our <a href="/health/water-intake" class="text-[var(--accent-color)] hover:underline font-semibold">Water Intake Calculator</a>.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Section 6: Meal Planning & Prep -->
    <section id="meal-planning" class="mb-12 scroll-mt-24">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mb-6 border-b border-[var(--border-color)] pb-2">6. Meal Planning & Prep</h2>
      <div class="space-y-4 text-[var(--text-secondary)]">
        <p>The best nutrition plan is the one you can actually stick to. Relying on willpower alone to cook healthy meals every night is a recipe for failure. Systematizing your food intake makes success automatic.</p>

        <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 my-6">
          <div>
            <h3 class="text-white font-bold mb-2">The Weekly Routine</h3>
            <ol class="list-decimal pl-5 space-y-2">
              <li><strong>Plan:</strong> Choose 3-4 core meals for the week. Keep breakfast and lunch repetitive to reduce decision fatigue.</li>
              <li><strong>Shop:</strong> Create a strict grocery list based on your macros and stick to the perimeter of the store (produce, meats, dairy).</li>
              <li><strong>Batch Cook:</strong> Prepare large quantities of proteins (e.g., chicken breasts, ground beef) and complex carbs (rice, quinoa) on Sunday.</li>
            </ol>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-[var(--bg-color)] p-5 rounded-lg border border-[var(--border-color)]">
            <h3 class="text-[var(--accent-color)] font-bold mb-2">Pro Tip</h3>
            <p class="text-sm">Don't try to make gourmet meals for meal prep. Think in terms of "components" rather than recipes: a protein source, a carb source, and a vegetable. Mix and match with different low-calorie sauces.</p>
            <p class="text-sm mt-3">Read our complete <a href="/health/guide-meal-prep" class="text-[var(--accent-color)] hover:underline font-bold">Guide to Meal Prep</a> for step-by-step strategies.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Section 7: Common Myths -->
    <section id="nutrition-myths" class="mb-12 scroll-mt-24">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mb-6 border-b border-[var(--border-color)] pb-2">7. Common Nutrition Myths</h2>
      <div class="space-y-6 text-[var(--text-secondary)]">

        <div class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] border-l-4 border-red-500 p-4 rounded-r-lg">
          <h3 class="text-white font-bold mb-1">Myth: Carbs Make You Fat</h3>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong>Truth:</strong> Overeating calories makes you fat. Carbohydrates do not inherently cause fat storage unless they put you in a caloric surplus.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] border-l-4 border-red-500 p-4 rounded-r-lg">
          <h3 class="text-white font-bold mb-1">Myth: You Must Eat 6 Small Meals a Day to "Stoke Your Metabolism"</h3>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong>Truth:</strong> The Thermic Effect of Food (TEF) is proportional to the total calories consumed, not the frequency. Six 500-calorie meals have the same TEF as three 1000-calorie meals.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] border-l-4 border-red-500 p-4 rounded-r-lg">
          <h3 class="text-white font-bold mb-1">Myth: Eating Late at Night Causes Fat Gain</h3>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong>Truth:</strong> Your body does not have a clock that suddenly stores calories as fat after 8 PM. Total daily caloric intake is what matters.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] border-l-4 border-red-500 p-4 rounded-r-lg">
          <h3 class="text-white font-bold mb-1">Myth: Supplements Are Necessary for Results</h3>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong>Truth:</strong> Supplements are exactly that—supplementary. Whey protein, creatine, and vitamins can be helpful conveniences, but real whole foods should make up 90% of your diet.</p>
        </div>

      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Section 8: FAQ -->
    <section id="faq" class="mb-12 scroll-mt-24">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mb-6 border-b border-[var(--border-color)] pb-2">8. Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div class="space-y-4">

        <div class="bg-[var(--bg-color)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-lg p-5">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-white mb-2">How many calories should I eat?</h3>
          <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)]">Your daily calorie needs depend on your Total Daily Energy Expenditure (TDEE). If you want to lose weight, eat 300-500 calories below your TDEE. To gain muscle, eat 200-500 calories above it. For maintenance, eat at your TDEE.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-[var(--bg-color)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-lg p-5">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-white mb-2">How much protein do I need per day?</h3>
          <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)]">For active individuals or those looking to build muscle, a standard recommendation is 0.7 to 1 gram of protein per pound of body weight. For general health, 0.4 to 0.5 grams per pound is sufficient.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-[var(--bg-color)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-lg p-5">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-white mb-2">How much water should I drink?</h3>
          <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)]">A general baseline is half your body weight in ounces per day, but you should add 16-24 oz per hour of intense exercise, especially in hot climates.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-[var(--bg-color)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-lg p-5">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-white mb-2">Do carbs make you fat?</h3>
          <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)]">No. Consuming more calories than you burn (a caloric surplus) is what causes weight gain. Carbs are simply a source of energy and do not inherently cause fat gain unless overconsumed.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-[var(--bg-color)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-lg p-5">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-white mb-2">Does meal timing matter?</h3>
          <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)]">For most people, overall daily caloric and macronutrient intake is far more important than exactly when you eat. Meal timing only becomes crucial for elite athletes or specific training regimens.</p>
        </div>

      </div>
    </section>

  </div>
</SiteLayout>
